%N A394981 Given a set of n rectangular tiles, {1 X 1, 1 X 2, 1 X 3, 1 X 4, ..., 1 X n}, then a(n) is the number of tilings up to symmetry of the rectangle having smallest possible perimeter with area n*(n+1)/2 using all n tiles.
%C A394981 The area is a triangular number. The only rectangle we are looking at is the one with the smallest perimeter. So, when n=8 the area is 36 and we are only counting the number of ways to use the tiles to make a 4 X 9 rectangle not 1 X 36, 2 X 18, nor 3 X 12 rectangles. That is, the short side of the rectangle has length floor((n+1)/2)).
%F A394981 Conjecture: If n is odd, then a(n+1) = 4*a(n).
%e A394981 For n=4, a(4)=4. The rectangle has area 10 = 2*5:
